			<p>Lunar New Year, commonly referred to as Spring Festival in China, is one of the most important festival for Chinese. Just like the Christmas is in the West, Spring Festival is the festival for Chinese people to be reunited with their families. <br>
			    Chinese New Year is associated with several myths and customs, in part because tt is the oldest festival in China. The festival was traditionally a time to honor deities as well as ancestors. <br>
			    In ancient times, people were afraid of the monster called a Nian. Every year, a Nian would come to harass people. Ancient people invented firecrackers to drive the monster away. This is the origin of the behavior that Chinese people set off firecrackers to celebrate Chinese New Year.<br>
			    Within China, regional customs and traditions concerning the celebration of the New Year vary widely. In the Chinese New Year period, the festival atmosphere are strong in everywhere. The day before the Lunar New Year is frequently regarded as an occasion for Chinese families to gather for the annual reunion dinner. <br>
			    Foods for Lunar New Year are different in north and south part of China. In northern China, dumplings is the indispensable food. In Southern China, people prefer wonton rather than dumplings.<br>
			    It is also traditional for every family to thoroughly clean their house, in order to sweep away any ill-fortune and to make way for incoming good luck. Usually Chinese people clean up all the places they need to clean before the New Year's Eve. <br>
			    Windows and doors are frequently decorated red paper-cuts and couplets. Popular themes among these paper-cuts and couplets include that of good fortune or happiness, wealth, and longevity. Other activities include lighting firecrackers and giving money in red paper envelopes.</p>
